WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.960
 - Hello, and welcome to our lecture on forms.

00:00:01.960 --> 00:00:04.280
 There's actually quite a few lectures here,

00:00:04.280 --> 00:00:07.240
 'cause we're gonna talk about how forms work in HTML and HTTP,

00:00:07.240 --> 00:00:10.480
 and then we're gonna talk about how they work in django.

00:00:10.480 --> 00:00:15.160
 So, forms are the way that we put HTML in browsers

00:00:15.160 --> 00:00:17.000
 that have fill-in-the-blank areas.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:21.000
 And so, the idea is that you draw some fields

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:22.560
 and some places for the user to type,

00:00:22.560 --> 00:00:25.560
 and then you have some way of sending the data

00:00:25.560 --> 00:00:26.520
 up to the server.

00:00:26.520 --> 00:00:29.720
 And so, we'll take a look at a number of different ways

00:00:29.720 --> 00:00:33.000
 to gather this stuff and send it to a server.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:36.280
 There are two basic ways to talk to the server

00:00:36.280 --> 00:00:38.120
 with form data.

00:00:38.120 --> 00:00:39.600
 We've been, everything we've been doing

00:00:39.600 --> 00:00:42.400
 when you do an anchor tag is a get request,

00:00:42.400 --> 00:00:45.360
 which means you're gonna get a document and show it.

00:00:45.360 --> 00:00:47.680
 And you can put parameters on the end of those,

00:00:47.680 --> 00:00:51.040
 like the question mark, question mark guess equals 42.

00:00:51.040 --> 00:00:53.360
 You can put that on the end of a URL.

00:00:53.360 --> 00:00:55.080
 But then, what we're gonna really introduce

00:00:55.080 --> 00:00:58.000
 and talk more about is the notion of posting data.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:02.200
 So, in forms, you can actually do getting or posting.

00:01:02.200 --> 00:01:05.680
 And so, let's take a look at some code here.

00:01:05.680 --> 00:01:10.040
 So, this is a little bit of utility code

00:01:10.040 --> 00:01:14.200
 that I'm gonna use over and over and over again

00:01:14.200 --> 00:01:17.680
 because the get data and the post data

00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:21.240
 and even the cookie data and stuff come in as dictionaries.

00:01:21.240 --> 00:01:23.160
 They look like dictionaries, key value pairs.

00:01:23.160 --> 00:01:26.240
 And so, I just wanted a way to dump the data.

00:01:26.240 --> 00:01:28.840
 I want a little label, probably should call that guy label,

00:01:28.840 --> 00:01:29.800
 and then a dictionary.

00:01:29.800 --> 00:01:32.960
 And so, I'm just gonna retrieve, go through all the items

00:01:32.960 --> 00:01:36.760
 and call HTML escape so that we just don't end up

00:01:36.760 --> 00:01:41.760
 with a cross-site scripting injection.

00:01:41.760 --> 00:01:43.280
 Just print the keys and values out

00:01:43.280 --> 00:01:45.040
 and put some paragraph tags and stuff like that.

00:01:45.040 --> 00:01:46.880
 So, it's just a way to dump this out

00:01:46.880 --> 00:01:49.160
 so I can show it to you and not put this code

00:01:49.160 --> 00:01:50.360
 on every one of my slides.

00:01:50.360 --> 00:01:53.280
 So, just remember that that's what dump data does.

00:01:53.280 --> 00:01:57.280
 And here is a little form that prints out a form

00:01:57.280 --> 00:01:59.440
 and then retrieves the form.

00:01:59.440 --> 00:02:00.880
 So, you'll note the dump data.

00:02:00.880 --> 00:02:02.800
 If there is no data in request.get,

00:02:02.800 --> 00:02:04.600
 it doesn't print anything out.

00:02:04.600 --> 00:02:08.120
 But this ends up producing a form, right?

00:02:08.120 --> 00:02:10.840
 And there's a form tag, there's an input tag.

00:02:10.840 --> 00:02:12.960
 Input is the painting.

00:02:12.960 --> 00:02:15.080
 Just put some text out and then this label,

00:02:15.080 --> 00:02:17.720
 this box here is the input type equals text name

00:02:17.720 --> 00:02:19.820
 equals guess, size equals 40,

00:02:19.820 --> 00:02:21.840
 and then we put a submit button out.

00:02:21.840 --> 00:02:24.520
 And we can type some stuff in and we can hit

00:02:24.520 --> 00:02:27.960
 the submit button, type 42 in, and hit submit button.

00:02:27.960 --> 00:02:31.320
 And you will notice that once this submit button is hit,

00:02:31.320 --> 00:02:34.840
 it adds automatically onto the end of the URL

00:02:34.840 --> 00:02:37.720
 that it came from, question mark guess equals 42.

00:02:37.720 --> 00:02:40.580
 And then it sends that back and does another get request,

00:02:40.580 --> 00:02:42.520
 but this time it does a get request

00:02:42.520 --> 00:02:44.320
 with question mark equals 42.

00:02:44.320 --> 00:02:46.600
 In comes this, this guess equals 42

00:02:46.600 --> 00:02:49.800
 is put onto the request.get and then we dump it out

00:02:49.800 --> 00:02:52.920
 so we get to see the key value pair of guess equals 42.

00:02:52.920 --> 00:02:55.880
 And again, Django's taking care of all that parsing

00:02:55.880 --> 00:02:57.940
 and everything before we get to it.

00:02:57.940 --> 00:03:01.880
 Now, this is pretty much the exact same thing.

00:03:01.880 --> 00:03:04.580
 Later we're gonna talk about this CSRF exempt.

00:03:04.580 --> 00:03:07.400
 This is to keep it as simple as possible for now.

00:03:07.400 --> 00:03:10.000
 And all we have to do is tell that we would like

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:12.840
 to communicate this same form of data,

00:03:12.840 --> 00:03:15.140
 one input field and a submit button.

00:03:15.140 --> 00:03:17.920
 We're gonna communicate this from the browser

00:03:17.920 --> 00:03:19.760
 to the server using the POST method.

00:03:19.760 --> 00:03:22.840
 So this is a communication to the browser

00:03:22.840 --> 00:03:25.860
 when the server says, I would like to send this data

00:03:25.860 --> 00:03:29.060
 using the technique of POST, not the technique of GET.

00:03:29.060 --> 00:03:32.880
 And so, you know, it prints out, we put in the number,

00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:35.120
 we submit it, and so the first thing that you'll notice

00:03:35.120 --> 00:03:38.320
 is there's no key value pairs, and that's because the POST

00:03:38.320 --> 00:03:40.640
 actually transports the data to the server

00:03:40.640 --> 00:03:41.800
 in a different way.

00:03:41.800 --> 00:03:45.840
 And it appears in a different key value pair.

00:03:45.840 --> 00:03:47.640
 We can tell whether it's a POST or a GET,

00:03:47.640 --> 00:03:49.400
 and if it's a GET, we get our GET parameters

00:03:49.400 --> 00:03:51.280
 in request.get, and if it's a POST,

00:03:51.280 --> 00:03:53.680
 we get our POST parameters in request.post.

00:03:53.680 --> 00:03:56.420
 And so we still get the same GUESS keyword

00:03:56.420 --> 00:03:59.620
 equals the number 42, okay?

00:03:59.620 --> 00:04:03.280
 And so that's simply the two ways of transporting it.

00:04:03.280 --> 00:04:05.880
 And this is talking about those two ways, right?

00:04:05.880 --> 00:04:09.200
 The browser has a form, you know, blah, blah, blah,

00:04:09.200 --> 00:04:12.360
 input type equals GUESS, and the name field,

00:04:12.360 --> 00:04:15.860
 name equals GUESS, is the field that is going to tell

00:04:15.860 --> 00:04:17.680
 what the key value pair is.

00:04:17.680 --> 00:04:21.040
 So if you're gonna put a POST, I mean, you're gonna hit

00:04:21.040 --> 00:04:24.680
 the submit button on a GET form, it does a GET

00:04:24.680 --> 00:04:26.760
 to wherever it came from, right?

00:04:26.760 --> 00:04:29.520
 And then it pens the key value pair to the end.

00:04:29.520 --> 00:04:31.840
 And again, that goes into Django, which parses it

00:04:31.840 --> 00:04:34.880
 and puts it in request.get, et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

00:04:34.880 --> 00:04:39.200
 And if all you do is you tell it with a method equals POST,

00:04:39.200 --> 00:04:40.860
 then it chooses a different way.

00:04:40.860 --> 00:04:43.780
 So the POST is going to the same URL,

00:04:43.780 --> 00:04:45.280
 but there are no parameters here,

00:04:45.280 --> 00:04:48.340
 and so there's a series of headers, like, you know,

00:04:48.340 --> 00:04:52.160
 what is my preferred language, et cetera, et cetera,

00:04:52.160 --> 00:04:56.220
 what I'm using for my browser, the content type

00:04:56.220 --> 00:04:58.440
 is this application URL form encoded,

00:04:58.440 --> 00:04:59.880
 and that's talking about this.

00:04:59.880 --> 00:05:02.320
 Now remember, this is going into the server,

00:05:02.320 --> 00:05:05.800
 so the content type coming out tells if it's an HTML page

00:05:05.800 --> 00:05:09.400
 or a JPEG, but the content type going in tells the browser,

00:05:09.400 --> 00:05:11.840
 tells the server how to parse this.

00:05:11.840 --> 00:05:14.480
 So it leaves a blank line, it's very symmetric

00:05:14.480 --> 00:05:16.980
 with how the server sends us pages back,

00:05:16.980 --> 00:05:18.840
 and then guess equals 42.

00:05:18.840 --> 00:05:21.120
 Now, there's some complexity here,

00:05:21.120 --> 00:05:24.460
 and there's some complexity in that POST data,

00:05:24.460 --> 00:05:27.360
 and there is some complexity in the GET parameters

00:05:27.360 --> 00:05:29.280
 where if you're sending special characters,

00:05:29.280 --> 00:05:31.000
 there's ways they have to be encoded,

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:32.240
 but we're gonna ignore that for now.

00:05:32.240 --> 00:05:35.280
 Just understand that the reason you don't see

00:05:35.280 --> 00:05:38.080
 the parameters on the POST request

00:05:38.080 --> 00:05:39.720
 is the data has been transported,

00:05:39.720 --> 00:05:42.920
 it is part of the HTTP connection,

00:05:42.920 --> 00:05:44.480
 and it's later on in the connection

00:05:44.480 --> 00:05:48.100
 after all the headers have been sent.

00:05:48.100 --> 00:05:51.000
 So you might say it doesn't matter.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:53.660
 Well, it does matter.

00:05:53.660 --> 00:05:55.280
 So there's a couple of simple rules.

00:05:55.280 --> 00:05:57.320
 The POST needs to be used when data

00:05:57.320 --> 00:05:59.000
 is going to be created or modified,

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:02.000
 and we'll see situations where we force this,

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:05.240
 where you don't wanna delete something on a GET request.

00:06:05.240 --> 00:06:09.440
 If you're reading or searching, GET is great.

00:06:10.660 --> 00:06:13.520
 It should never be used to insert, modify, or delete data,

00:06:13.520 --> 00:06:16.120
 anything that's gonna change the state of the system,

00:06:16.120 --> 00:06:18.440
 and part of the problem is that

00:06:18.440 --> 00:06:20.240
 web spiders will find GET requests.

00:06:20.240 --> 00:06:22.960
 So you might, if you build a bad application,

00:06:22.960 --> 00:06:26.740
 like a catalog of bearings, for example,

00:06:26.740 --> 00:06:31.160
 and you have a delete that happens to be a GET request,

00:06:31.160 --> 00:06:36.160
 and a web spider grabs your page and hits all those URLs,

00:06:36.160 --> 00:06:37.900
 you might find that the web spider

00:06:37.900 --> 00:06:39.780
 just wiped out your database.

00:06:39.780 --> 00:06:42.720
 So web spiders do not follow POSTs

00:06:42.720 --> 00:06:44.440
 because they assume that by following POST,

00:06:44.440 --> 00:06:46.920
 they might be changing your data, but by following GETs,

00:06:46.920 --> 00:06:47.880
 they're just reading your data,

00:06:47.880 --> 00:06:50.520
 and that's all a web spider really wants to do,

00:06:50.520 --> 00:06:53.360
 unless, of course, it's doing some kind of automation.

00:06:53.360 --> 00:06:57.040
 So GET URLs are supposed to be idempotent.

00:06:57.040 --> 00:07:00.720
 So the idea is if you say blah, blah, blah,

00:07:00.720 --> 00:07:02.600
 guess equals 42, it's supposed to kind of

00:07:02.600 --> 00:07:04.160
 give you back the same page.

00:07:04.160 --> 00:07:09.160
 Now, that's like saying blah, blah, blah, current calendar,

00:07:09.680 --> 00:07:11.080
 well, what is the current calendar?

00:07:11.080 --> 00:07:13.380
 It might be, it's not identical,

00:07:13.380 --> 00:07:15.720
 but it is sort of semantically the same thing.

00:07:15.720 --> 00:07:18.120
 So you're supposed to be able to go bookmark a GET.

00:07:18.120 --> 00:07:19.920
 You can bookmark a GET URL,

00:07:19.920 --> 00:07:24.560
 but not like you might say, where's my inbox?

00:07:24.560 --> 00:07:27.200
 Here's a URL to my inbox in some kind of a system

00:07:27.200 --> 00:07:28.640
 to read my data.

00:07:28.640 --> 00:07:31.140
 And so you can bookmark that and go back to your inbox.

00:07:31.140 --> 00:07:32.860
 It should be a GET request.

00:07:32.860 --> 00:07:35.040
 You shouldn't be bookmarking POSTs.

00:07:35.040 --> 00:07:37.640
 The other thing is that depending on your browser,

00:07:37.640 --> 00:07:40.440
 your web server software, et cetera,

00:07:40.440 --> 00:07:42.280
 you may have an upper limit on the GET.

00:07:42.280 --> 00:07:44.680
 Let's just think 2,000 characters.

00:07:44.680 --> 00:07:47.000
 Doesn't mean you should worry about it too much,

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:48.560
 but just large things,

00:07:48.560 --> 00:07:51.480
 especially when we start uploading files like pictures,

00:07:51.480 --> 00:07:53.960
 then all of a sudden the GET is impossible

00:07:53.960 --> 00:07:55.320
 and you have to use POST.

00:07:55.320 --> 00:07:57.080
 And it also has the advantage that POST

00:07:57.080 --> 00:08:00.200
 doesn't mess up your, it keeps your URLs looking prettier.

00:08:00.200 --> 00:08:02.440
 So next we're just gonna do a quick review

00:08:02.440 --> 00:08:05.600
 of the kinds of things that you can do in forms and HTML

00:08:05.600 --> 00:08:08.620
 and different kind of input tags we can show in our HTML.

00:08:08.620 --> 00:08:11.200
 (upbeat music)

